{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"Wire the two-scope gate posture across the three gates, plumb resolution-class + sanitized diagnostic through the two verdict-returning gates, define the exit-11 contract, own the shared-file (runner.py) module-size reconciliation, enforce never-certify structurally, wrap the MCP failure surface, and document the model. Lands LAST (wave 3); INTEGRATION OWNER for the seams the other children touch.\n\n## Why\nThe three gates must share a systemic *block-but-retryable* posture while PRESERVING per-criterion fail-open, carry `resolution_class` + `diagnostic` so routing and troubleshooting both work, expose a distinct-but-grounded exit code, never sign a degraded result, and tell the human exactly what to do.\n\n## What\n\n### Two-scope posture\nA **systemic** failure → block-but-retryable (exit 11, unsigned) across the gates; a **per-criterion** failure → drop-and-continue fail-open (one flaky finder among N must NOT block a claim — PRESERVED, regression-tested). Make code-review match plan-review's existing systemic block; turn completion's fail-closed-as-FAIL into a distinct retryable exit (NOT a verification FAIL, which means \"your work is wrong\").\n\n### The single source of retryability: `LLMOutcome`\nmamba's `classify_llm_failure` returns an `LLMOutcome` with `resolution_class` (the closed 8-value enum) AND a pre-computed `retryable: bool`. Everything downstream reuses BOTH — the write-sites persist both into `coverage`; the CLIs read the persisted `retryable` bool directly and never re-derive retryability by string-comparing the class name.\n\n### Two data-flow shapes\n- **Shape A — plan-review + code-review return a DEGRADED VERDICT DICT.**\n  - **Write-site:** `gate_dispatch._degraded_plan_review_verdict` / `_degraded_code_review_verdict` read `outcome = getattr(error, 'outcome', None)` off the caught `error` and, WHEN PRESENT, set `coverage['resolution_class'] = outcome.resolution_class.value`, `coverage['diagnostic'] = outcome.diagnostic`, and `coverage['retryable'] = outcome.retryable`.\n  - **Reachability (verified):** `produce_plan_review_verdict` calls the helper three ways: `preflight` failure (`error=exc`), mid-run `LLMUnavailableError` (`error=exc`), and the finders-failed tail (`error=res.error`, a STRING). TODAY only mamba's run-seam attaches `.outcome`; `PydanticAIRunner.preflight` raises WITHOUT it. So this story ALSO attaches `.outcome` in `preflight` — `raise LLMUnavailableError(...)` becomes `exc.outcome = classify_llm_failure(exc, ClassifyContext(...)); raise exc` — so the common pre-call outage carries disposition too. The write-site reads `getattr(error,'outcome',None)`: present on the two exception paths (preflight now included), absent on the string finders-failed tail (→ plain INDETERMINATE, exit 2, correct — a finders-produced-nothing failure is not classified transient).\n  - **code-review translation:** `rebar.llm.review_code` returns a `review_result` TRANSLATED from the gate `code_review_verdict` by `shim._verdict_to_review_result`. That translator is updated to COPY the gate verdict's `coverage` (with `resolution_class`/`retryable`/`diagnostic`) to the TOP-LEVEL `review_result['coverage']`, so `_review_code()` reads `result.get('coverage',{}).get('retryable')` directly (mirroring `_review_plan`).\n- **Shape B — completion-verify FAILS by RAISING `LLMUnavailableError`** (no verdict dict). `transition_close._completion_precheck` (line ~174) has a broad `except Exception as exc: raise CommandError(...) from None` that TODAY discards the exception + its `.outcome`. Fix (SINGLE mechanism — no subclass, no new attribute): in `_completion_precheck`, before building the message, compute `_o = getattr(exc, 'outcome', None)` and `rc = 11 if (_o and _o.retryable) else 1`, then `raise CommandError(<class-specific message>, returncode=rc) from None`. `CommandError` already carries `returncode`, and `transition.py` already returns `exc.returncode` to the process — so exit 11 propagates with no plumbing change. There are TWO shape-B CLI surfaces with DISTINCT mechanisms: (a) the `rebar close`/transition path (`close_ticket`→`_completion_precheck`→`CommandError(returncode=11)`, above); (b) the standalone `rebar verify-completion` (`_verify_completion()`), whose OWN `except llm.LLMError as exc: return 1` arm (`_llm_commands.py` ~line 305) catches `LLMUnavailableError` directly — so THAT arm is updated to `_o=getattr(exc,'outcome',None); return 11 if (_o and _o.retryable) else 1`. Both shape-B arms also write the sanitized diagnostic to the session log (see below).\n\n### Exit-code-11 contract\nRetryable (`_o.retryable`, i.e. `WAIT_AND_RETRY`/`RETRY_NOW`) → exit **11** (\"transient — retry\", NEW). Any other non-null disposition → the gate's EXISTING INDETERMINATE exit. Null disposition → the existing PASS/BLOCK exit.\n- **Exit 2 is NOT redefined.** `review-plan` ALREADY exits 2 for INDETERMINATE (pinned by arawana); UNCHANGED. Only the retryable subset is peeled to 11.\n- **CLI sites (`_llm_commands.py`):** `_review_plan()` (shape A; tail currently `0/1/2` — extended to add 11) and `_review_code()` (shape A; TODAY always returns 0 on any verdict — updated to distinguish `0/1/2/11` off the preserved `coverage`). Shape B surfaces through TWO CLI entrypoints: `rebar verify-completion` (`_verify_completion()`) AND the `rebar close` / `rebar transition … closed` path (which reaches `close_ticket` → `_completion_precheck`; `transition.py` returns the `CommandError.returncode`, so exit 11 flows there too). `_review()` (the per-ticket `review_ticket` advisory reviewer) is NOT a site.\n- **Message delivery:** the class-specific message (table below) is printed to STDERR as the line `llm-degrade: <resolution_class> — <message>` — shape B embeds it in the `CommandError` message; shape A renders it in `_review_plan`/`_review_code` from `coverage['resolution_class']` via a `_RESOLUTION_MESSAGES` lookup dict (the table below, keyed by class name).\n- **Worked example:** a 429 degraded plan-review carries `coverage.retryable=True, resolution_class='WAIT_AND_RETRY'` → `_review_plan` exits 11; a 429 during `rebar close` raises `LLMUnavailableError`, `_completion_precheck` reads `.outcome.retryable` → `CommandError(returncode=11)` → the close exits 11 (fail-closed, unsigned).\n\n### Per-class actionable messages (ResolutionClass → stderr text)\n| ResolutionClass | Message |\n|---|---|\n| `WAIT_AND_RETRY` | Transient provider overload/rate-limit — wait for the backoff window, then retry. |\n| `RETRY_NOW` | Transient connection blip — retry immediately. |\n| `INCREASE_PROVIDER_LIMITS` | Provider usage/quota ceiling hit — raise the provider limit or wait for the reset. |\n| `CHANGE_SETTINGS` | The request exceeded a configured bound (tokens/steps/timeout) — adjust it and retry. |\n| `CHANGE_INPUT` | The input was rejected (too large / malformed) — reduce or fix it and retry. |\n| `CHANGE_PROVIDER_OR_MODEL` | The model/provider is unavailable or refused — switch model/provider. |\n| `FIX_AGENT_DESIGN` | An agent-construction bug (no tools / bad output contract) — fix the op wiring. |\n| `NEEDS_INVESTIGATION` | Unclassified failure — inspect the sanitized diagnostic. |\n\n### Verdict-schema field (the two verdict-returning gates only)\nAdd OPTIONAL `coverage.resolution_class` (enum, 8 values), `coverage.retryable` (bool), `coverage.diagnostic` (sanitized object) to `plan_review_verdict.schema.json` and `code_review_verdict.schema.json` (their `coverage` is already `additionalProperties:true`, so this is documentary; readers tolerate unknown keys — forward/rollback-safe). **`completion_verdict.schema.json` is NOT changed** (shape B surfaces via the raised `.outcome`, no verdict dict — a field there would be dead). Sole writer of the schema edits.\n\n### Session-log diagnostic write (calling convention, both shapes)\nAt each degrade site (shape A helpers AND the shape-B `_completion_precheck` arm), call `rebar.append_session_log(entry, summary=…, relates_to=<ticket_id>)` where `entry = json.dumps(sanitized_diagnostic, sort_keys=True)` (the sanitized dict, never the raw exception), `summary = f\"llm-degrade {resolution_class} on <gate>\"`, `relates_to` = the reviewed ticket id when available. Wrapped best-effort (`try/except Exception`): a session-log failure must NEVER fail the gate (regression-tested).\n\n### Never-sign guard + pre-sign fingerprint recheck (at the CALLER, not generic `sign_manifest`)\n`signing.sign_manifest(ticket_id, manifest)` is a generic multi-caller primitive with no verdict in scope, so the guards live at the SIGN-DECISION callers:\n- **Never-sign guard:** at the plan-review sign path (`review_plan`) and the completion sign path (`close_ticket`), refuse to CALL `sign_manifest` when `verdict.get(\"verdict\") != \"PASS\"` OR `verdict.get(\"coverage\",{}).get(\"resolution_class\")` is set. This makes the existing \"degraded ⇒ unsigned\" invariant STRUCTURAL (regression-tested). It introduces no new unsigned state (INDETERMINATE is already unsigned).\n- **Pre-sign fingerprint recheck:** \"material fingerprint\" = the committed head SHA the verdict was verified against, which is ALREADY carried in the returned manifest as its `verified-at-sha:<sha>` step (`_verdict_manifest`). In `close_ticket`, INSIDE the write lock, immediately before calling `sign_manifest`, extract that sha from the manifest and compare it to a fresh `signing.head_sha(repo_root)` read; on mismatch (code drifted during the retry/timeout-widened verify→sign window) SKIP signing. The ticket STILL closes (the transition already committed) — this is the same closed-without-signature outcome as `--force-close`/`local`-source, so the close command EXITS 0 with a stderr warning \"closed without a completion signature (code drifted between verify and sign)\". Verify itself stays OUTSIDE the write lock (`transition_close` ordering preserved; asserted).\n\n### MCP structured failure return (`_mcp_llm.py`)\nThe write-gated MCP tools (`review_plan`, `review_code`, `verify_completion`) in `src/rebar/_mcp_llm.py` today `return rebar.llm.X(...)` and let a raised `LLMError`/`LLMUnavailableError` propagate as a FastMCP tool ERROR (opaque to the agent). Wrap each body: on a raised `LLMError`, RETURN a structured result dict `{\"error\": str(exc), \"resolution_class\": <cls or None>, \"retryable\": <bool>, \"diagnostic\": <sanitized>}` (disposition read from `getattr(exc,'outcome',None)`), so the driving agent can branch on `retryable` instead of parsing an error string. (Shape-A tools already return a degraded verdict dict; this closes the shape-B/hard-error raise.)\n\n### Integration ownership (shared files)\nrunner.py's module-size allowlisting (allowlist + ceilings 850 + `docs/architecture.md` remedy row) ALREADY LANDED with the anole commit in this stack (visible at `--ref HEAD`), so it is NOT a deliverable here. This story owns the final runner.py reconciliation (the `preflight` `.outcome` attachment above) and the taxonomy/retry/timeout docs, and lands LAST.\n\n## Scope\n- `gate_dispatch.py` degrade write-sites; `code_review/shim.py` (`_verdict_to_review_result` coverage preservation); `transition_close.py` (`_completion_precheck` returncode-11 + shape-B session-log; `close_ticket` never-sign guard + in-lock fingerprint recheck) preserving verify-outside-lock ordering; `_llm_commands.py` exit-11 mapping (`_review_plan`/`_review_code`/`_verify_completion`); `_mcp_llm.py` structured-failure wrap; `signing.py` (only if a caller-side helper is factored — the guard lives at the callers); the two verdict JSON schemas; `docs/exit-codes.md`; `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_exit_codes.py`; `docs/adr/`.\n- NOT in scope: removing/weakening per-criterion fail-open; changing `completion_verdict.schema.json`; changing `sign_manifest`'s signature.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `_review_plan()` exits 11 when the verdict's `coverage.retryable` is true.\n- [ ] `_review_plan()` exits 2 (existing INDETERMINATE) when INDETERMINATE and `coverage.retryable` is false/absent.\n- [ ] `_review_code()` distinguishes `0/1/2/11` off the preserved `coverage` (it currently always returns 0).\n- [ ] `shim._verdict_to_review_result` preserves `coverage.resolution_class`/`retryable`/`diagnostic` onto the returned `review_result`.\n- [ ] `_completion_precheck` raises `CommandError(returncode=11)` when the caught exception's `.outcome.retryable` is true, else `returncode=1`.\n- [ ] `PydanticAIRunner.preflight` attaches `.outcome` (via `classify_llm_failure`) to its raised `LLMUnavailableError`, so preflight outages carry disposition.\n- [ ] `_verify_completion()`'s `except llm.LLMError` arm returns 11 when `.outcome.retryable` is true, else 1.\n- [ ] The `rebar close` / transition CLI path surfaces that returncode (exit 11) unchanged via `transition.py`.\n- [ ] A degraded / INDETERMINATE verdict is emitted unsigned (never-sign guard at the caller refuses to call `sign_manifest`; regression test).\n- [ ] The pre-sign head-SHA fingerprint (from the manifest's `verified-at-sha:` step) is re-checked inside the write lock immediately before signing; a mismatch closes unsigned and the close command exits 0 with a stderr warning (test for the mismatch path).\n- [ ] Verify remains OUTSIDE the write lock (`transition_close` ordering asserted by a test).\n- [ ] A degraded verdict/close prints the class-specific message (from the table) to stderr.\n- [ ] The sanitized diagnostic is written to the session log at BOTH the shape-A and shape-B degrade sites via `append_session_log(json.dumps(diagnostic, sort_keys=True), summary=…, relates_to=…)`, best-effort (a session-log failure does not fail the gate; regression test).\n- [ ] `coverage.resolution_class` (enum), `coverage.retryable` (bool), `coverage.diagnostic` (object) are optional properties on `plan_review_verdict.schema.json` and `code_review_verdict.schema.json`; `completion_verdict.schema.json` is unchanged.\n- [ ] The shape-A write-site copies `resolution_class`/`retryable`/`diagnostic` from the caught error's `.outcome` when present (outage paths); the string-error finders-failed path yields a plain INDETERMINATE.\n- [ ] Per-criterion fail-open preserved: a single flaky finder among N does not block (regression test).\n- [ ] `_mcp_llm.py`'s `review_plan`/`review_code`/`verify_completion` return a structured failure dict `{error,resolution_class,retryable,diagnostic}` on a raised `LLMError` instead of propagating a FastMCP tool error (test for a degraded sub-path).\n- [ ] `docs/exit-codes.md` gains a recorded-decision entry defining exit 11; `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_exit_codes.py` pins 11.\n- [ ] The exit-11 ADR (sections: Context, Decision — 11=block-but-retryable distinct from 2, Consumers+additive-safety, Rollback) enumerates consumers: the driving agent/human (docs/exit-codes.md), CI (`.github/workflows/gerrit-verify.yaml`, `test.yml` — any-non-zero-is-failure, never invokes the gate CLIs so 11 is invisible to Verified), the review-bot (`src/rebar/review_bot/adapter.py` — votes off the verdict dict, tolerates open coverage keys); each additive-safe; rollback = retryable falls back to the existing INDETERMINATE exit (no data migration).\n- [ ] The diagnostic-sanitization ADR (sections: Context, Allowlist + redaction rules, Threat model — keys/PII/hex/base64/email must never leak, Test coverage) is authored.\n- [ ] `make lint`, `make typecheck`, `make test` are all green.\n\n## Verified structural facts (experiment log — repo snapshot, offline)\n```\nShape-B: transition_close.py::_completion_precheck (line ~174 broad except → CommandError from None discards .outcome; fix sets returncode from .outcome.retryable). CommandError (_commands/_seam.py) already carries returncode; transition.py returns exc.returncode (lines ~359/467).\nShape-A: gate_dispatch.py::_degraded_plan_review_verdict/_degraded_code_review_verdict. Called 3x: preflight (error=exc), mid-run (error=exc) → .outcome present; finders-failed (error=res.error STRING) → no .outcome → plain INDETERMINATE.\ncode-review CLI: rebar.llm.review_code → shim._verdict_to_review_result (translates verdict→review_result; must preserve coverage). _review_code currently returns 0 for any verdict.\nCLI arms: _llm_commands.py::_review_plan (tail 0/1/2), _review_code, _verify_completion. rebar close/transition → close_ticket → _completion_precheck.\nSchemas (coverage additionalProperties:true): plan_review_verdict.schema.json, code_review_verdict.schema.json (edited); completion_verdict.schema.json unchanged.\nSigning: signing.py::sign_manifest(ticket_id, manifest) generic multi-caller; guard + head_sha recheck live at callers (review_plan sign path, close_ticket) — verify OUTSIDE write lock.\nMCP: _mcp_llm.py review_plan/review_code/verify_completion return rebar.llm.X(...) (raise propagates as FastMCP error today).\nConsumers: CI .github/workflows/gerrit-verify.yaml + test.yml (make targets, not gate CLIs); review-bot src/rebar/review_bot/adapter.py (verdict dict, not exit codes).\nExit contract: docs/exit-codes.md (0/1/2/10 frozen 2026-06-09) pinned by tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_exit_codes.py; 11 additive.\n```\nAdditive/rollback-safe: schema fields optional; exit 11 additive. Records the two NEW ADRs (exit-11, diagnostic-sanitization); transport-retry (0037) + async-watchdog (0038) already exist. Owns runner.py module-size reconciliation. Lands LAST."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783691869199433001,"uuid":"9516511f-f83f-46bc-9cb0-8305393a0277"}